            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-1" xml:lang="en">leveling pillar</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">pingzhu</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">平柱</term>
            <term xml:id="term-feature_name-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">平柱</term>
            <gloss>In traditional Chinese timber-frame architecture, refers to two eaves pillars
               framing the central bay on the sides of the building parallel to the roof ridge.
               Leveling pillars are used as a standard height for calculating the height of other
               pillars across the façade, as they increase in height from the center towards the
               corners of the building, allowing for an upward curvature of the eaves (shengqi). The
               term appears in the Yingzao Fashi (1103, SKQS ed., 5.4b) and also in documents
               written by officials during the Song Dynasty (960-1279) to describe the architecture
               of mausolea. Modern architectural historians use this term to describe central-bay
               pillars on all sides of a building dating from the Tang (618-907) to early Ming
               (1368-1644) dynasties. (ATTCAT Project)</gloss>
